<div id="content" lang="en" dir="ltr">
<a href="./MayLith">MayLith</a>: When playing the game, I find that in-game alphabetical help index extremely useful. <p>
Do we duplicate it (more or less) here on the wiki? (I can't believe I'm even asking that question, as it's even <em>more</em> work, but it's got to be asked.)  
</p>
<p>
<a href="./MassimilianoMarangio">MassimilianoMarangio</a>: I don't think that an index is needed for normal words, since you can always search for pages that contain the word.  
</p>
<p>
(Discussion about categories moved to <a href="./Wiki_20Suggestions_2fAdditional_20Categories">Wiki Suggestions/Additional Categories</a>) 
</p>
<p>
Back to the topic: There is already an indexing function in the wiki <a href="./TitleIndex">TitleIndex</a> and <a href="./WordIndex">WordIndex</a>. It is possible to restrict them to all subpages of Documentation? This would solve the indexing problem. 
</p>
<p>
<a href="./MayLith">MayLith</a>: Ah! I didn't realize <a href="./TitleIndex">TitleIndex</a> and <a href="./WordIndex">WordIndex</a> existed.  
</p>
<p>
If it could be restricted to subpages of Documentation, that would be perfect. If not, we could still add a brief reference with a warning that some search results might be Spoilers. Not ideal, but...  
</p>
<p>
(Side issue... I just peeked at <a href="./WordIndex">WordIndex</a>. Should we be deleting all that German stuff?) 
</p>
<p>
<a href="./MassimilianoMarangio">MassimilianoMarangio</a>: The index is generated automatically, i.e. we need either to remove the non-english documentation pages or to restrict the index to non-system pages as the standard <a href="./TitleIndex">TitleIndex</a> page. 
</p>
